Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a broad range of ideas in practice ranging from technology push or technological imperative to the strict sense that human destiny is determined by an underlying logic associated with the laws of science and its manifestation in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general notions: on the one hand, that the development of technology itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural or political influence; and on the other hand, that technology itself has “effects” on societies that is more inherently than socially conditioned than on the other hand, that it is the same; and, on the other hand, that it is the same; and, on the other hand, that it is the same; and, on the other hand, that
For example, one can claim that the passenger car inevitably entails the development of roads.
However, a nationwide road network for only a small number of cars is economically unsustainable; therefore, new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car ownership.
The widespread car ownership also leads to a higher number of accidents on the roads, which in turn leads to the invention of new health-care techniques to repair damaged bodies.
