The Sundarbans are the largest mangrove belt in the world and extend over 80 km from the Bangladeshi and Indian hinterland to the coastline.
The Sundarbans have been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site, part of the forest, located within the Indian state, is called the Sundarbans National Park.
The forests, however, are not only mangrove swamps — they also include some of the last remaining holdings of the mighty jungle, which once covered the Ganges Plains.
The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which one third is covered by water and marches.
The Sundarbans have been a nature reserve since 1966, and it is estimated that 400 Bengal king tigers and about 30,000 spotted deer are now kept there.
